'''Marguerite Wyke''' '''[[OBE]]''' (May 1908 – 1995) was an [[African-American]]-born Trinidadian teacher, poet, artist and politician. After growing up in Jersey City, New Jersey, and working as a teacher, she married and moved to Canada for a decade and then relocated to Trinidad. Writing for various journals and newspapers, and cultivating the artistic community in Trinidad, she became active in local politics. Renouncing her U. S. citizenship, Wyke became a Trinidadian citizen in 1953 and became active in the island's governance. With the establishment of the [[West Indies Federation]] she was appointed as one of two Senators from [[Trinidad and Tobago]] and one of only two women Senators to serve in the federal parliament. When the Federation dissolved, Wyke returned to her artistic endeavors, publishing poetry and participating in various art media.

==Early life==
Marguerite N. Abrams was born in May 1908 in New Jersey to Jessie B. M. (née Wardlaw) and James Edward Abrams.{{sfn|New Jersey State Census|1915|p=A4}}{{sfn||New York Marriages|1907}}{{sfn|U. S. Census|1910|p=7A}} She was the oldest child of the [[Pullman porter]], James,{{sfn|U. S. Census|1910|p=7A}}{{sfn|Hogans|1926|p=9}} having younger siblings James Jr. and Bessie{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}}{{sfn|U. S. Census|1930|p=1A}} (or Jessie).{{sfn|U. S. Census|1920|p=20B}} Abrams graduated from [[Lincoln High School (New Jersey)|Lincoln High School]] in 1926{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}}{{sfn|''The New York Age''|1926|p=8}} and then went on to study at [[New York University]]. Simultaneously taking art courses at the [[Grand Central School of Art]], she graduated with a degree in English literature.{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}}{{sfn|''The New York Age''|1932|p=1}} Continuing her studies, Abrams completed a teaching degree at the [[New Jersey City University|New Jersey State Normal School at Jersey City]].{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}}{{sfn|''The New York Age''|1933|p=2}}

==Career==
By 1929, Abrams was working as a teacher in the [[Jersey City Public Schools|Jersey City Public School System]].{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}}{{sfn|''The New York Age''|1929|p=9}} Abrams began publishing poetry, in such journals as ''Opportunity Magazine''{{sfn|''The New York Age''|1932|p=1}}{{sfn|''The New York Age''|1929|p=9}} and taught until her marriage on 18 February 1933 to David Arnold Wyke. He was a Trinidadian physician who at the time of their marriage was working in [[Toronto]], Ontario, Canada as the only black physician in the city.{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}}{{sfn|''The New York Age''|1932|p=1}}{{sfn|''The New York Age''|1933|p=2}} The young couple moved to Toronto after their marriage where David continued his work as a doctor and Marguerite continued publishing, contributing to the ''[[Canadian Forum]]''.{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}} The couple were part of the politically active [[Black Canadians|West Indian community]] living in Toronto. While her husband was [[politically conservative]], Wyke's politics were leftist and she joined the [[Co-operative Commonwealth Federation]] (CCF) while living in Canada.{{sfn|Lambton|2003|p=196}}

In 1946, the couple relocated to Trinidad, where Wyke became affiliated with the [[Caribbean Socialist Party]]. Continuing her writing, she published articles for ''The Teachers Herald'', the journal of the Teacher's Economic and Cultural Association (TECA).{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}} In 1952, she and her husband traveled to Europe for further education. While he studied in Scotland, she attended courses at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] in Paris{{sfn|Thomas|1952|p=18}} and also studied under [[Étienne Martin]] at the Académie Ronson.{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}} Wyke also took courses and graduated from the [[University of the West Indies]].{{sfn|''Caribbean Quarterly''|2008|p=205}} She actively cultivated development of the arts in Trinidad, serving as a committee member of the Trinidad and Tobago Art Society, of which she became vice president in 1956.{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}} She brought artists and writers, like [[Karl Broodhagen]] and [[Langston Hughes]] to Trinidad.{{sfn|''A Challenging Endeavor''|2002|p=13}}{{sfn|''Jet''|1959|p=41}}

In 1953, Wyke [[renunciation of United States citizenship|renounced her US citizenship]] to become a Trinidadian citizen,{{sfn|''Ebony''|1960|p=57}} with the intent of helping [[Eric Williams]] in his rise to prominence. She was involved in the PNM from early days, making speeches, serving on committees and writing for the newspaper.{{sfn|Cartwright|1958|p=12}} In the mid-1950s, she worked with working-class women through the projects of the Women's League for the [[People's National Movement]] (PNM).{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}} She assisted in the compilation of reports evaluating the Trinidadian economy and society and served on the committee which analyzed appointing [[Caribbean people|West Indians]] to positions to govern their own affairs.{{sfn|''The Gleaner''|1958b|p=14}} During the same time frame, Wyke worked on the planning of the Caribbean Festival of the Arts and made several trips to other islands to attend music and art festivals.{{sfn|Cartwright|1958|p=12}}

When the [[West Indies Federation]] was established in 1958, Wyke was appointed as one of the two women Senators to serve in the national parliament of the new federal state. Wyke represented [[Trinidad and Tobago]] along with Deonarayan Maharajh and the other woman Senator was [[Bertha Higgins]] of [[Antigua and Barbuda]].{{sfn|''The Gleaner''|1958b|p=14}}{{sfn|''The Gleaner''|1958a|p=1}} She actively pursued legislation to secure the rights of West Indians, working on legislation to fight racism, including urging the [[British parliament]] to protect Caribbeans living in Britain{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}}{{sfn|''The Gleaner''|1960|p=16}} and protect workers from exploitative recruitment policies.{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}} Wyke was opposed to free movement among the Caribbean islands, fearing that large influxes of people would over-tax limited resources.{{sfn|''The Gleaner''|1961|p=11}} She also worked to establish the first art scholarships on the island to help young artists gain their education{{sfn|''A Challenging Endeavor''|2002|p=21}} and protested the use of women in beauty contests held to improve tourism prospects.{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}}

After her service in the Senate, Wyke returned to artistic pursuits and promoting development of the arts, as well as heritage protection programs.{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}} In 1961, she exhibited works for the opening of Nina's Art Gallery, one of the first galleries to open in Trinidad.{{sfn|Collier|2013|p=404}} She was chair of the committee organized to prepare for the celebrations of Trinidad and Tobaggo's Independence, which featured a [[Calypso music|calypso]] competition.{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}} Wyke was appointed an [[Order of the British Empire|Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] in 1963 for her service to Trinidad as chair of the Independence Celebrations Committee.{{sfn|''The London Gazette''|1962|p=51}}{{sfn|''The Dominica Herald''|1963|p=8}} In the 1970s, Wyke served as the chair of the advisory board to the Central Library of Trinidad and Tobago.{{sfn|''The World of Learning''|1972|p=1258}}

In her lifetime, though Wyke worked in multiple artistic media, including fused glass, mosaic, painting, and pottery,{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}} she was most known for her sculpture.{{sfn|''Caliban''|1975|p=53}} She produced works which are held in private collections throughout the Caribbean, Canada, Denmark and the United States.{{sfn|''Caribbean Quarterly''|2008|p=205}}

==Death and legacy==
Wyke died around 1995.{{sfn|Sindoni|2016}} In 2002, the Cultural Center Art Gallery of the [[Inter-American Development Bank]] in Port of Spain, hosted an art exhibition for the country's 40th anniversary of independence. Wyke was one of several featured artists included in the show.{{sfn|''A Challenging Endeavor''|2002|pp=7, 36}}

